{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:41:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:41:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.77,0.07,0,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79604"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64908"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"937"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11284"},{"type":"tags","id":"11288"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27220"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79604"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is completing a clinical placement at a teaching hospital. During a ward round, they see an interesting case and want to discuss it with their study group.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate way to share the clinical case details electronically?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Send patient information via personal email","Share anonymised details using an approved secure platform","Store case details in a password-protected document","Post case details on a private social media group","Keep clinical photographs without identifiable features on personal phone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate approach is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eshare anonymised details using an approved secure platform\u003C/strong\u003E. This ensures patient confidentiality while allowing legitimate educational discussion. Any patient information shared must be de-identified and transmitted through platforms that meet healthcare privacy and security requirements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options violate patient privacy and confidentiality principles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESend patient information via personal email\u003C/strong\u003E - Personal email accounts lack required security features for healthcare communications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStore case details in a password-protected document\u003C/strong\u003E - Password protection alone does not meet healthcare security standards and does not address secure transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost case details on a private social media group\u003C/strong\u003E - Social media platforms, even private groups, are not secure for sharing patient information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeep clinical photographs without identifiable features on personal phone\u003C/strong\u003E - Clinical photographs may only be kept for educational purposes with explicit patient consent and complete removal of identifiers occurs in accordance with hospital policies and privacy laws; simply removing identifiable patient features is insufficient if patients have not been appropriately consented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers must protect patient confidentiality in all forms of communication. Electronic sharing of health information requires secure, encrypted platforms and explicit patient consent for any identifiable details.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers must obtain explicit patient consent before sharing any identifiable health information electronically.","Medical communications must use secure, encrypted platforms that comply with health information privacy laws.","Patient confidentiality requirements apply equally to electronic and physical medical records and communications."],"references":["Medical Indemnity Industry Association of Australia. Clinical images and the use of personal mobile devices [internet]. [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available from: https://ama.com.au/sites/default/files/documents/FINAL_AMA_Clinical_Images_Guide.pdf.","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64908"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64908"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T10:29:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T10:30:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11563"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79604"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,